  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The autumn public holiday cluster in Queensland (Easter and Anzac Day) reliably disrupts the rhythm of a sale campaign for a four-week window every year. For sellers, the choice is not whether to acknowledge it but how to plan around it. Campaigns designed thoughtfully around this window can use the holiday cluster strategically. Campaigns that ignore it lose attendance, momentum, and signal at the most expensive weeks of the marketing spend.</p>

      <p>This article walks through what happens to buyer behaviour during the cluster, the strategic launch options sellers can choose between, what to avoid, and how to keep a campaign moving through the holiday window if it is already in market. The 2028 dates are used throughout as a worked example.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The 2028 calendar in detail</h2>
      <p>In 2028 specifically, the autumn public holiday cluster lands as follows. Good Friday is April 14, Easter Saturday is April 15, Easter Sunday is April 16, and Easter Monday is April 17, producing a four-day Easter long weekend. Anzac Day falls on Tuesday April 25, a single public holiday eight days after Easter Monday. The Queensland school holidays around Easter typically run for two weeks centred on the long weekend, putting families in and out of town from roughly the start of April through the end of the third week of April. The net effect is an effectively disrupted four-week period from late March to late April.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens to buyer behaviour through the cluster</h2>
      <p>Open home attendance reliably drops thirty to sixty per cent on long weekends, and falls further on the Saturdays immediately before and after Easter as buyers travel for holidays or wind down in the days before the break. Online portal enquiry typically holds up better, because buyers continue to research properties from holiday locations and during downtime, but the conversion of online enquiry to physical inspection slows through the cluster. Agents reduce contact volume through the long weekends. Auction calendars typically pause for Easter weekend itself, with most auction houses moving any auctions scheduled near Easter to the following Saturday. Conveyancers, solicitors, mortgage brokers, banks, and building and pest inspectors all run on reduced capacity through the cluster, which lengthens contract timelines for any deals signed in the lead-up.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The three strategic launch options</h2>
      <p>Sellers planning a campaign with launch in or near the autumn cluster have three realistic strategic options.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Option one: launch before the Easter cluster.</strong> Going to market in March or very early April allows the first two weekends of the campaign to capture buyer attention before the holiday disruption begins. The contract conditional period can then run through the holidays, with finance, building and pest, and other contingencies progressing on extended timelines. This option works well for properties where the marketing story is strong enough to capture serious interest in the first two weekends. The risk is that the campaign loses momentum if it has not produced offers before the long weekend hits.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Option two: launch immediately after Easter.</strong> Going to market in the week of April 18 to 24 (the week after Easter Monday and before Anzac Day in 2028) launches into a fresh, holiday-rested buyer pool. Online enquiry tends to spike in this week as buyers return from holidays and re-engage with their property search. The catch is that Anzac Day (Tuesday April 25 in 2028) still mildly disrupts week two of the campaign, and the second weekend of the campaign (April 29 to 30) is the first fully clean weekend.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Option three: launch in May.</strong> Going to market clear of the holiday cluster entirely produces a clean four-week campaign window without disruption, but the broader autumn buyer surge has typically peaked by late April, and the May market starts to pivot toward the cooler winter rhythm. This option suits sellers who can use the additional time for preparation rather than launching into a compressed window.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The post-Easter rebound weekend</h2>
      <p>The first weekend after Easter (April 22 to 23 in 2028) is consistently one of the strongest weekends for buyer activity in the autumn calendar. Buyers are refreshed from the break, ready to re-engage, and the listing inventory is often thinner than normal because other sellers have either pulled forward their launch (option one above) or held back (option three). Properties that launch on this weekend can attract a disproportionate share of agent and buyer attention, which is exactly the dynamic sellers want for their first open home.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to avoid</h2>
      <p>Three avoidable mistakes account for most of the campaign damage that happens around the autumn cluster. First, do not schedule the first open home for an Easter long weekend (Good Friday Saturday or Easter Saturday). Attendance will be low, the photography of an empty open home tells the wrong story, and the campaign loses early momentum that is hard to recover. Second, do not schedule auction for Easter Sunday or Easter Monday. Auction houses typically refuse these dates anyway, but sellers occasionally push for them; they should be moved to the following Saturday without exception. Third, do not pause the campaign through the cluster as if the property has been withdrawn from the market. Buyers can still inspect by appointment, online enquiry continues, and a campaign that goes silent for two weeks signals weakness. Maintain visible activity even if the public open home schedule is reduced.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The marketing rhythm during the cluster</h2>
      <p>For campaigns that are already in market when the cluster arrives, the practical playbook is to maintain visibility while flexing the open home schedule. The listing stays active on portals throughout the cluster. Open homes are scheduled for the Saturdays that are not long weekends (April 8 in 2028 if pre-cluster, April 22 if post-Easter, April 29 clear of Anzac Day). Private inspections continue for serious buyers willing to engage during the holidays, including during school holiday weeks where families specifically use the break to compress their property search. Communication with all interested buyers continues through the cluster so the campaign does not appear stalled. Marketing spend on portals and social media continues through the period, recognising that some of the enquiry will land but convert later.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The price guide and reserve discussion</h2>
      <p>If the campaign is heading to auction post-Easter, the reserve should be set on the basis of the pre-Easter buyer feedback and comparable sales evidence, not on the assumption that the holiday break has shifted the market. The break itself does not move underlying demand or comparable sales values; it just compresses the window in which buyers are physically inspecting. A reserve set lower because of a perceived "Easter softness" is usually leaving money on the table. The same applies to private treaty pricing: the price expectation set going into the campaign should hold through the cluster unless there is direct buyer feedback telling a different story.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The family buyer dynamic during school holidays</h2>
      <p>The Queensland school holidays around Easter produce an unusual buyer dynamic that often runs counter to the general assumption that holidays are quiet. Families with school-age children frequently use the break specifically to inspect properties (without the weekday school run pressure), particularly families relocating from interstate who use the holiday window to compress their Brisbane property search into a one-week trip. For catchment-zone properties in family-oriented inner-east suburbs (Bulimba, Hawthorne, Norman Park, parts of Camp Hill, parts of Coorparoo), open homes during school holiday Saturdays can be busier than equivalent term-time Saturdays. This is a meaningful segment for the right property type and should not be discounted.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>The summary position is that the autumn public holiday cluster should be treated as a planned disruption to design around, not as a cancellation of the market. Campaigns can be designed to launch before or after the cluster, or to run through it with adjusted open home rhythm. The worst outcomes come from campaigns that launch directly into the long weekends without adjustment, or that schedule auction dates on Easter Sunday, Easter Monday, or Anzac Day. The strongest outcomes come from campaigns that either complete before Easter, launch into the post-Anzac window, or use the post-Easter rebound weekend as their first open home. The right answer for any specific property depends on preparation timing, the suburb's typical buyer rhythm, and whether the property type benefits from the family buyer cohort that engages during school holidays.</p>

